### Describe the bug

Hello.
When using Python 3.13.0a1 and Cython 3.0.5 to build grpc 1.48.4 with [a Cython 3 patch](https://src.fedoraproject.org/rpms/grpc/raw/8bf11b8c20d2c54dcf7b88777d7590237b6b0555/f/0001-Specify-noexcept-for-cdef-functions.patch). I see a GCC 12+ C++17 error:

```
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp: At global scope:
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:1360:31: error: standard attributes in middle of decl-specifiers
 1360 |         #define CYTHON_UNUSED [[maybe_unused]]
      |                               ^
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:5501:12: note: in expansion of macro ‘CYTHON_UNUSED’
 5501 |     static CYTHON_UNUSED PyObject *__Pyx_KwargsAsDict_FASTCALL(PyObject *kwnames, PyObject *const *kwvalues);
      |            ^~~~~~~~~~~~~
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:1360:31: note: standard attributes must precede the decl-specifiers to apply to the declaration, or follow them to apply to the type
 1360 |         #define CYTHON_UNUSED [[maybe_unused]]
      |                               ^
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:5501:12: note: in expansion of macro ‘CYTHON_UNUSED’
 5501 |     static CYTHON_UNUSED PyObject *__Pyx_KwargsAsDict_FASTCALL(PyObject *kwnames, PyObject *const *kwvalues);
      |            ^~~~~~~~~~~~~
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:1360:31: warning: attribute ignored [-Wattributes]
 1360 |         #define CYTHON_UNUSED [[maybe_unused]]
      |                               ^
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:5501:12: note: in expansion of macro ‘CYTHON_UNUSED’
 5501 |     static CYTHON_UNUSED PyObject *__Pyx_KwargsAsDict_FASTCALL(PyObject *kwnames, PyObject *const *kwvalues);
      |            ^~~~~~~~~~~~~
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:1360:31: note: an attribute that appertains to a type-specifier is ignored
 1360 |         #define CYTHON_UNUSED [[maybe_unused]]
      |                               ^
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:5501:12: note: in expansion of macro ‘CYTHON_UNUSED’
 5501 |     static CYTHON_UNUSED PyObject *__Pyx_KwargsAsDict_FASTCALL(PyObject *kwnames, PyObject *const *kwvalues);
      |            ^~~~~~~~~~~~~
```

This builds fine with Python 3.12.0 as the problematic code is only `#if CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_CPYTHON && PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x030d0000` as added in https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/5767 and located at:

https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/e6094e2211b3528f49c6c383c47fae96de3b65de/Cython/Utility/FunctionArguments.c#L507-L508

Unfortunately, I don't understand what the error means, so I am unable to suggest a fix.,

### Code to reproduce the behaviour:

```
$ podman run --rm -ti fedora:rawhide /usr/bin/bash
...
# dnf -y install abseil-cpp-devel c-ares-devel re2-devel openssl-devel zlib-devel gcc-c++ git-core python3.13-devel
...
# git clone https://github.com/hroncok/grpc.git --branch cython-reporducer --depth 1
...
# cd grpc/
# python3.13 -m venv venv
# . venv/bin/activate
(venv) # pip install setuptools cython==3.0.5
...
(venv) # GRPC_PYTHON_BUILD_SYSTEM_ABSL=1 GRPC_PYTHON_BUILD_SYSTEM_RE2=1 GRPC_PYTHON_BUILD_SYSTEM_ZLIB=1 GRPC_PYTHON_BUILD_SYSTEM_OPENSSL=1 GRPC_PYTHON_BUILD_SYSTEM_CARES=1 GRPC_PYTHON_BUILD_WITH_CYTHON=1 python setup.py build_ext
...
gcc -fno-strict-overflow -Wsign-compare -DDYNAMIC_ANNOTATIONS_ENABLED=1 -DNDEBUG -fcf-protection -fexceptions -fcf-protection -fexceptions -fcf-protection -fexceptions -fPIC -D_WIN32_WINNT=1536 -DGRPC_XDS_USER_AGENT_NAME_SUFFIX=\"Python\" -DGRPC_XDS_USER_AGENT_VERSION_SUFFIX=\"1.48.4\" -DOPENSSL_NO_ASM=1 -DGPR_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_MODE=1 -DHAVE_CONFIG_H=1 -DGRPC_ENABLE_FORK_SUPPORT=1 "-DPyMODINIT_FUNC=extern \"C\" __attribute__((visibility (\"default\"))) PyObject*" -DGRPC_POSIX_FORK_ALLOW_PTHREAD_ATFORK=1 -Isrc/python/grpcio -Iinclude -I. -I/usr/include -Ithird_party/address_sorting/include -I/usr/include -I/usr/include/re2 -I/usr/include/openssl -Ithird_party/upb -Isrc/core/ext/upb-generated -Isrc/core/ext/upbdefs-generated -Ithird_party/xxhash -I/usr/include -I/grpc/venv/include -I/usr/include/python3.13 -c src/core/plugin_registry/grpc_plugin_registry.cc -o python_build/temp.linux-x86_64-cpython-313/src/core/plugin_registry/grpc_plugin_registry.o -std=c++17 -fvisibility=hidden -fno-wrapv -fno-exceptions -pthread
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:2252:72: warning: ‘Py_UNICODE’ is deprecated [-Wdeprecated-declarations]

      |                                                                        ^

                 from /usr/include/python3.13/Python.h:59,

src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:1365:31: note: an attribute that appertains to a type-specifier is ignored
 1365 |         #define CYTHON_UNUSED [[maybe_unused]]
      |                               ^
src/python/grpcio/grpc/_cython/cygrpc.cpp:5506:12: note: in expansion of macro ‘CYTHON_UNUSED’
 5506 |     static CYTHON_UNUSED PyObject *__Pyx_KwargsAsDict_FASTCALL(PyObject *kwnames, PyObject *const *kwvalues);
```

No GCC errors.

### OS

Fedora Linux 40

comment_data.body:
> https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/e6094e2211b3528f49c6c383c47fae96de3b65de/Cython/Utility/FunctionArguments.c#L507-L508
> 
> Unfortunately, I don't understand what the error means, so I am unable to suggest a fix.,

From some casual research, I think that (for GCC 12 or later and C++17 or later, both of which are in play here) the standard attribute needs to go before rather than after `static`. There are quite a few commits of that nature in various projects. I haven’t found a citation for why this is needed in terms of the C++ standard or GCC release notes.

I have a reproducer that works outside of RPM environment. It uses code from https://github.com/hroncok/grpc/tree/cython-reporducer which is slightly patched from usptream's v1.48.4. I edited it into the initial report. It uses Fedora Rawhide podman container to fetch build dependencies, but if you know how to fetch them on your distro, should be reproducible there as well assuming your GCC is new enough (mine isn't on Fedora 37).

Anyway, does this boils down to:

```patch
-static CYTHON_UNUSED PyObject ...
+CYTHON_UNUSED static PyObject ...
```

?

I will try that.
